	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>malloc Problem</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">char *RAM = &#40;char *&#41;malloc&#40;0x800&#41;;</div><br /><br />Instead of having char, it gives me int, and I must have the following to cater.<br /><br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">CPU.Databus = &#40;unsigned char&#41;CPU.ROMPointer1&#91;&#40;CPU.PC &amp; 0x1FFF&#41;&#93;;</div>
<br />
<br />Without the (unsigned char), it returns $0FFFFFA9 instead of just plain $A9. Is it normal for malloc to use int instead of char? If not, how can I get around this?

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>mic_</b> [ Thu May 15, 2008 4:08 am ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />malloc just gives you an address to the allocated memory, it doesn't care about if you're going to store ints or chars in that memory.
<br />
<br />if CPU.Databus is an int you will get a sign-extension when reading from an 8-bit variable, unless you specifically state otherwise with a cast.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>tepples</b> [ Thu May 15, 2008 4:48 am ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Try using 'unsigned char *RAM' instead of 'char *RAM' to avoid having to cast away the sign extension every time.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>blargg</b> [ Thu May 15, 2008 7:24 am ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />The "char" type is either signed or unsigned, depending on the compiler (it's often signed). Since even the number of bits in a char (CHAR_BIT) is up to the compiler, the clearest way to request an 8-bit byte (octet) is with the uint8_t type from &lt;stdint.h&gt;.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
